<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Scientific Notation</h1>=20


<p><b>Scientific Notation</b> (also called <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfu=
n.com/algebra/standard-form.html">Standard Form</a> in Britain) is a specia=
l way of writing numbers:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">Like this:</td>
			<td style=3D"width:30px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
numbers/images/scientific-notation-a.svg" alt=3D"scientific notation 700 =
=3D 7x10^2 hdr" height=3D"51" width=3D"257"></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"width:30px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">Or this:</td>
			<td style=3D"width:30px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
numbers/images/scientific-notation-b.svg" alt=3D"scientific notation 4,900,=
000,000 =3D 4.9x10^9" height=3D"53" width=3D"391"></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>It makes it easy to use very large or very small values.</p>=20


<h2>OK, How Does it Work?</h2>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 700</h3>=20

	<p>Why is 700 written as <span class=3D"center"><b>7 =C3=97 10<sup>2</sup>=
</b> in Scientific Notation ?</span></p>=20
	<div class=3D"so"> 700 =3D 7 =C3=97 100</div>
<div class=3D"so">and 100 =3D 10<sup>2</sup> <i>(see <a href=3D"https://www=
.mathsisfun.com/index-notation-powers.html">powers of 10</a>)</i>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"so">so 700 =3D <b>7 =C3=97 10<sup>2</sup></b></div>
<p class=3D"center">Both <b>700</b> and <b>7 =C3=97 10<sup>2</sup></b> have=
 the same value, just shown in different ways.</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 4.900.000.000</h3>=20

	<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; 1.000.000.000 =3D 10<sup>9</sup> ,<br>
so 4.900.000.000 =3D <b>4,9 =C3=97 10<sup>9</sup></b> in Scientific Notatio=
n</p>=20
	</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/physics/imag=
es/moon-full.jpg" alt=3D"moon" height=3D"185" width=3D"187"></div>

<h3>Example: It is about 385.000.000 m from the Earth to the Moon</h3>=20

<p>&nbsp;100.000.000 =3D 10<sup>8</sup> ,<br>
385.000.0000 =3D <b>3,85 =C3=97 10<sup>8</sup></b> in Scientific Notation</=
p>=20
</div>=20

<p class=3D"larger">The number is written in <b>two parts</b>:</p>=20
<div class=3D"bigul">=20
<ul>=20
	<li>Just the <b>digits</b>, with the decimal point placed after the first =
digit, followed by</li>=20
	<li><b>=C3=97 10 to a <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/index-notation=
-powers.html">power</a></b> that puts the decimal point where it should be<=
br>
(i.e. it shows how many places to move the decimal point).</li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>=20

<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/s=
cientific-notation.svg" alt=3D"scientific notation 5326.6 =3D 5.3266x10^3" =
height=3D"91" width=3D"318"><br>
In this example, 5326,6 is written as <b>5,3266 =C3=97 10<sup>3</sup></b>,<=
br>
because 5326,6 =3D 5,3266 =C3=97 1000 =3D 5,3266 =C3=97 10<sup>3</sup></p>=
=20


<h2>Try It Yourself</h2>=20

<p>Enter a number and see it in Scientific Notation:</p>=20

<iframe width=3D"100%" height=3D"165" scrolling=3D"no" title=3D"JavaScript =
Animation" style=3D"display: block; margin: auto; border: none; background-=
color: transparent; overflow: hidden; transition: 0.6s ease-in-out; max-wid=
th: 100%;"></iframe><div class=3D"script" style=3D"height: 165px; display: =
none;">images/sci-notation.js</div>
<p>Now try to use Scientific Notation yourself:</p>=20

<iframe width=3D"798" height=3D"165" scrolling=3D"no" title=3D"JavaScript A=
nimation" style=3D"display: block; margin: auto; border: none; background-c=
olor: transparent; overflow: hidden; transition: 0.6s ease-in-out; max-widt=
h: 100%;"></iframe><div class=3D"script" style=3D"height: 165px; display: n=
one;">images/sci-notation-num.js</div>


<h2>Other Ways of Writing It</h2>=20

<p class=3D"floatRt"><b style=3D"font: 36px Arial; color: blue;">3,1 =C3=97=
 10^8</b></p>=20
<p>We can use the <b>^</b> symbol (above the 6 on a keyboard), as it is eas=
y to type.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: <b>3 =C3=97</b> <b>10^4 is the same as 3 =C3=97 10<sup>4</sup=
></b></h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center large">3 =C3=97 10^4 =3D 3 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 1=
0 =C3=97 10 =3D 30.000</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Calculators often use "E" or "e" like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/c=
alculator-e-notation.jpg" alt=3D"calculator E notation" height=3D"50" width=
=3D"200"></p>=20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: <b>6E+</b><b>5 is the same as 6 =C3=97 10<sup>5</sup></b></h3=
>=20

	<p class=3D"center large">6E+5 =3D 6 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 =
10 =C3=97 10 =3D 600.000</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: <b>3,12E4</b><b> is the same as 3,12 =C3=97 10<sup>4</sup></b=
></h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center large">3,12E4 =3D 3,12 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 10 =
=C3=97 10 =3D 31.200</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>How to Do it</h2>=20

<p class=3D"center"><b>To figure out the power of 10, think "how many place=
s do I move the decimal point?"</b></p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style/left-arrow.gif" =
alt=3D"left arrow" height=3D"46" width=3D"46"></td>
			<td>When the number is 10 or greater, the decimal point has to move <b>t=
o the left</b>, and the power of 10 is <b>positive</b>.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style/right-arrow.gif"=
 alt=3D"right arrow" height=3D"46" width=3D"46"></td>
			<td>=20
<p>When the number is smaller than 1, the decimal point has to move <b>to t=
he right</b>, so the power of 10 is <b>negative</b>.</p></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 0,0055 is written <b>5,5 =C3=97 10<sup>-3</sup></b></h3>=20

	<p><br>
Because 0,0055 =3D 5,5 =C3=97 0,001 =3D 5,5 =C3=97 10<sup>-3</sup></p>=20
	</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 3,2 is written <b>3,2 =C3=97 10<sup>0</sup></b></h3>=20

	<p><br>
We didn't have to move the decimal point at all, so the power is <b>10<sup>=
0</sup></b></p>=20
	<p>But it is now in Scientific Notation</p>=20
	</div>


<h2>Check!</h2>=20

<p>After putting the number in Scientific Notation, just check that:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>The "digits" part is between 1 and 10 (it can be 1, but never 10)</li>=
=20
	<li>The "power" part shows exactly how many places to move the decimal poi=
nt</li>=20
</ul>=20


<h2>Why Use It?</h2>=20

<p>Because it makes it easier when dealing with very big or very small numb=
ers, which are common in Scientific and Engineering work.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: it is easier to write (and read) 1,3 =C3=97 10<sup>-9</sup> t=
han 0,0000000013</h3>=20

	</div>
<p>It can also make calculations easier, as in this example:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: a tiny space inside a computer chip has been measured to be 0=
,00000256m wide, 0,00000014m long and 0,000275m high.</h3>=20

	<p><b>What is its volume?</b></p>=20
	<p>Let's first convert the three lengths into scientific notation:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>width: 0,000 002 56m =3D 2,56=C3=9710<sup>-6</sup></li>=20
		<li>length: 0,000 000 14m =3D 1,4=C3=9710<sup>-7</sup></li>=20
		<li>height: 0,000 275m =3D 2,75=C3=9710<sup>-4</sup></li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>Then multiply the digits together (ignoring the =C3=9710s):</p>=20
	<p>2,56 =C3=97 1,4 =C3=97 2,75 =3D 9,856</p>=20
	<p>Last, multiply the =C3=9710s:</p>=20
	<p>10<sup>-6</sup> =C3=97 10<sup>-7</sup> =C3=97 10<sup>-4</sup> =3D 10<su=
p>-17</sup> (easier than it looks, just <b>add =E2=88=926, =E2=88=924 and =
=E2=88=927</b> together)</p>=20
	<p class=3D"larger">The result is <b>9,856=C3=9710<sup>-17</sup> m<sup>3</=
sup></b></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>It is used a lot in Science:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/physics/imag=
es/sun-horizon.jpg" alt=3D"sun"></div>
	<h3>Example: Suns, Moons and Planets</h3>=20

	<p>Our Sun has a Mass of 1,988 =C3=97 10<sup>30</sup> kg.</p>=20
	<p>Easier than writing 1.988.000.000.000.000.000.000.000.000.000 kg<br>
(and that number gives a false sense of many digits of accuracy.)</p>=20
	</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td>=20

<h3>Play With It!</h3>=20

<p>Use Scientific Notation<br>
in <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/gravity-freeplay.html">Gra=
vity Freeplay</a></p></td>
			<td><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/gravity-freeplay.html"=
><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/gravity-freeplay-thu=
mb.gif" alt=3D"gravity freeplay" height=3D"103" width=3D"245"></a></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>It can also save space! Here is what happens when you double on each squ=
are of a chess board:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/c=
hess-board-double.svg" alt=3D"Chess board doubling" height=3D"410" width=3D=
"410"><br>
Values are rounded off, so 53.6870.912 is shown as just 5=C3=9710<sup>8</su=
p></p>=20
<p>That last value, shown as 9=C3=9710<sup>18</sup> is actually 9.223.372.0=
36.854.775.808</p>=20


<h2>Engineering Notation</h2>=20

<p>Engineering Notation is like Scientific Notation, except that we only us=
e powers of ten that are multiples of 3 (such as 10<sup>3</sup>, 10<sup>-3<=
/sup>, 10<sup>12</sup> etc).</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Examples:</h3>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li>2.700 is written <b>2,7 =C3=97 10<sup>3</sup></b></li>=20
		<li>27.000 is written <b>27 =C3=97 10<sup>3</sup></b></li>=20
		<li>270.000 is written <b>270 =C3=97 10<sup>3</sup></b></li>=20
		<li>2.700.000 is written <b>2,7 =C3=97 10<sup>6</sup></b></li>=20
	</ul>=20
	</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 0,00012 is written <b>120 =C3=97 10<sup>-6</sup></b></h3>=20

	</div>
<p>Notice that the "digits" part can now be between 1 and 1.000 (it can be =
1, but never 1.000).</p>=20
<p>The advantage is that we can replace the <b>=C3=9710</b>s with <a href=
=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/metric-numbers.html">Metric Numbers</a>. So =
we can use standard words (such as thousand or million), prefixes (such as =
kilo, mega) or the symbol (k, M, etc)</p>=20
<div class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images=
/metric-prefixes.svg" alt=3D"metric prefixes" height=3D"84" width=3D"397"><=
br>
Powers of 3 fit our <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/metric-numbers.ht=
ml">metric number</a> system neatly:<br>
10<sup>6</sup> is <b>mega</b>, 10<sup>3</sup> is <b>kilo</b>, 10<sup>-3</su=
p> is <b>milli</b>, etc.

</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: 19.300 meters is written <b>19,3 =C3=97 10<sup>3</sup> m, or 1=
9,3 km</b></p>=20
	</div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: 0,00012 seconds is written <b>120 =C3=97 10<sup>-6</sup> s, or=
 120 microseconds</b></p>=20
	</div>
